<example id="fs-id1168345559782">
<exercise id="fs-id1168345544152"><problem id="fs-id1168345544154">
<para id="fs-id1168345544157">The perimeter of a rectangular swimming pool is 150 feet. The length is 15 feet more than the width. Find the length and width.</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1168345543026">
<title>Solution</title>
<table id="eip-id1167267897499" class="unnumbered unstyled can-break" summary="We are given a table with directions on the left and mathematical steps on the right. Step 1. Read the problem. Draw the figure and label it with the given information. To the right we have a rectangle with length w plus 15 and width w. Below this, we have P equals 150 ft. Step 2. Identify what you are looking for. To the right of this, we have the length and width of the pool. Step 3. Name. Choose a variable to represent it. To the right of this, we have let w equal the width. The length is 15 feet more than the width; hence, we let w plus 15 equal the length. Step 4. Translate. Write the appropriate formula and substitute in the given information. To the right of this, we have P equals 2L plus 2W. Below this, we have 150 equals 2 times the quantity (w plus 15) plus 2w. Step 5. Solve the equation. To the right of this, we have 150 equals 2w plus 30 plus 2w. Below this, we have 150 equals 4w plus 30. Below this, 120 equals 4w. Below this 30 equals w. Below this the length is determined: w plus 15, so 30 plus 15 equals 45. Step 6. Check. To the right of this, we have P equals 2L plus 2W. Below this we have 150 equals with a question mark over it 2 times 45 plus 2 times 30. Below this, we have 150 equals 150. Step 7. Answer the question: The length of the pool is 45 feet, and the width is 30 feet.">
